Hypotheses 
H1 .Tool Overload Reduces Efficiency
The presence of multiple dashboards that provide inconsistent or contradictory information likely reduces operator efficiency and increases cognitive load.
H2 .Outdated Documentation Causes Errors
When internal documents are not updated in sync with system or policy changes, employees may follow incorrect procedures, leading to operational mistakes and slower issue resolution.
H3 . Unstructured Onboarding Leads to Slow Skill Development
A lack of structured onboarding, training pathways, and guided mentorship likely delays new employees’ ability to perform independently and confidently.
H4 . Informal Communication Channels Increase Operational Risk
Relying on group chats for critical updates increases the chance that employees may miss important information, causing inconsistent performance and preventable errors.
H5 . Manual Cross Checking Increases Resolution Time
The need to manually cross verify alarms and dashboards likely increases average handling time and delays customer issue resolution.
H6 . Customer Complaints Are Harder to Address Due to Limited Diagnostic Tools
Insufficiently detailed or unclear customer-level diagnostic tools likely make it harder to accurately assess complaints, contributing to longer resolution times and customer dissatisfaction.
H7 . High Workload Uncertainty Elevates Stress Levels
Erratic shift intensity (chill vs warzone) and high-pressure situations likely contribute to emotional fatigue, stress, and burnout risk.
H8 . Lack of Centralized Knowledge Base Creates Dependency on Senior Staff
When information is scattered and documentation outdated, employees rely heavily on senior colleagues, creating knowledge gaps and bottlenecks.
H9 . Low Transparency in Tools Reduces Trust in Automation
If tools or future AI systems do not clearly explain how outputs are generated, employees will likely distrust recommendations and continue relying on manual judgment.
H10 . Process Inconsistency Decreases Employee Confidence
Frequent rule changes and unclear escalation pathways likely cause uncertainty, hesitation and fear of making mistakes among junior staff.
H11 . Repetitive Manual Tasks Create Inefficiency
Recurring incident patterns handled manually (duplicate alarms) likely lead to wasted time and reduced productivity.
H12 . Centralized Dashboard Could Improve Workflow
Introducing a single integrated dashboard could significantly reduce cognitive load, cross-checking time and operational errors.
